      </table>
    </table-wrap>
  </sec>
</sec>
<sec id="example-based-explainability-module">
  <title>Example-based explainability module</title>
  <sec id="formulation-1">
    <title>Formulation</title>
    <p>The <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\texttt{ExampleExplanation}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="monospace">𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎𝙴𝚡𝚙𝚕𝚊𝚗𝚊𝚝𝚒𝚘𝚗</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    module of <monospace>WoodTapper</monospace> is independent of the
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\texttt{RulesExtraction}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="monospace">𝚁𝚞𝚕𝚎𝚜𝙴𝚡𝚝𝚛𝚊𝚌𝚝𝚒𝚘𝚗</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    module and provides an example-based explainability. It enables
    tree-based models to identify the most similar training samples to
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[x]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>,
    using the similarity measure induced by generalized random forests
    (<xref alt="Athey et al., 2019" rid="ref-grf" ref-type="bibr">Athey
    et al., 2019</xref>;
    <xref alt="Breiman, 2001" rid="ref-breiman2001random" ref-type="bibr">Breiman,
    2001</xref>). For a new sample <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[x]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    with unknown label and a decision tree
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\mathcal{T}_m]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:msub><mml:mi>𝒯</mml:mi><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>,
    let <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\mathcal{L}_m(x)]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>ℒ</mml:mi><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    denote the set of training samples that share the same leaf as
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[x]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>.
    We define the similarity <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[w(x,x_i)]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>w</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    between <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[x]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    and <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[x_i]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    as: <disp-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[
    w(x,x_i) = \frac{1}{M} \sum_{m=1}^{M} \frac{\mathbb{1}_{\{x_i \in \mathcal{L}_m(x)\}}}{|\mathcal{L}_m(x)|}.
    ]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="block" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>w</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:mfrac><mml:munderover><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi></mml:munderover><mml:mfrac><mml:msub><mml:mn>𝟙</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">{</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>ℒ</mml:mi><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">|</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>ℒ</mml:mi><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">|</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mi>.</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></disp-formula></p>
    <p>Finally, the <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[l]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>l</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    training samples with the highest <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[w(x,x_i)]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>w</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    values, along with their target values
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[y_i]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:msub><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>,
    are shown as the examples that best explain the prediction of
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[x]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>x</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    by the tree-based ensemble model.</p>
    <p>In Python, the <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\textit{skgrf}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="italic">𝑠𝑘𝑔𝑟𝑓</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    (<xref alt="Flynn, 2021" rid="ref-skgrf" ref-type="bibr">Flynn,
    2021</xref>) package is an interface for using the R implementation
    of generalized random forest, focusing on classifiers for specific
    learning tasks (causal inference, quantile regression,…). For each
    task, the user can compute the kernel weights, equivalent to our
    leaf frequency match introduced above. Thus, we compare the kernel
    weights computation by <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\textit{skgrf}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="italic">𝑠𝑘𝑔𝑟𝑓</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    and our module. We stress the fact that our
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\texttt{ExampleExplanation}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="monospace">𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎𝙴𝚡𝚙𝚕𝚊𝚗𝚊𝚝𝚒𝚘𝚗</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    is designed for usual tree-based models such as random forests or
    extra trees and not specifically in a context of causal inference or
    quantile regression. In particular, the tree building of our forest
    is different from the one in <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\textit{skgrf}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="italic">𝑠𝑘𝑔𝑟𝑓</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec id="running-time-1">
    <title>Running time</title>
    <table-wrap>
      <caption>
        <p><bold>Comparison of GRF weight computations in several Python
        packages.</bold><styled-content id="tabU003Acomparison-grf"></styled-content></p>
      </caption>
      <table>
        <colgroup>
          <col width="30%" />
          <col width="38%" />
          <col width="31%" />
        </colgroup>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th><bold>Feature</bold></th>
            <th><bold><monospace>WoodTapper</monospace> (Py)</bold></th>
            <th><bold>skgrf (Py)</bold></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Forest implementation</td>
            <td><monospace>scikit-learn</monospace></td>
            <td><monospace>ranger</monospace></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Language</td>
            <td>Python</td>
            <td>Python &amp; R</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Package availability</td>
            <td>PyPI (<monospace>woodtapper</monospace>)</td>
            <td>PyPI (<monospace>skgrf</monospace>)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>scikit-learn API compatible</td>
            <td><inline-formula><alternatives>
            <tex-math><![CDATA[\checkmark]]></tex-math>
            <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>✓</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula></td>
            <td><inline-formula><alternatives>
            <tex-math><![CDATA[\checkmark]]></tex-math>
            <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>✓</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Tree-based models</td>
            <td>All</td>
            <td>Tree and random forest</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>GRF</td>
            <td><inline-formula><alternatives>
            <tex-math><![CDATA[\times]]></tex-math>
            <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>×</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula></td>
            <td><inline-formula><alternatives>
            <tex-math><![CDATA[\checkmark]]></tex-math>
            <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>✓</mml:mi></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </table-wrap>
    <p>In figure
    <xref alt="[fig:run-time-grf]" rid="figU003Arun-time-grf">[fig:run-time-grf]</xref>,
    we compare the kernel weight computation runtime of
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\texttt{ExampleExplanation}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="monospace">𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎𝙴𝚡𝚙𝚕𝚊𝚗𝚊𝚝𝚒𝚘𝚗</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    and <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\textit{skgrf}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="italic">𝑠𝑘𝑔𝑟𝑓</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    (<xref alt="Flynn, 2021" rid="ref-skgrf" ref-type="bibr">Flynn,
    2021</xref>) using the same hardware as previous experiments.
    <inline-formula><alternatives>
    <tex-math><![CDATA[\texttt{ExampleExplanation}]]></tex-math>
    <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="monospace">𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎𝙴𝚡𝚙𝚕𝚊𝚗𝚊𝚝𝚒𝚘𝚗</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
    is consistently faster.</p>
    <fig>
      <caption><p>Weights computation running time for simulated data
      using.<styled-content id="figU003Arun-time-grf"></styled-content></p></caption>
      <graphic mimetype="application" mime-subtype="pdf" xlink:href="run-time-grf-dim-log.pdf" />
    </fig>
  </sec>
</sec>
<sec id="ai-usage-disclosure">
  <title>AI usage disclosure</title>
  <p>Generative AI tools were used in this software only to implement
  the Cython function in the <inline-formula><alternatives>
  <tex-math><![CDATA[\texttt{ExampleExplanation}]]></tex-math>
  <mml:math display="inline" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mtext mathvariant="monospace">𝙴𝚡𝚊𝚖𝚙𝚕𝚎𝙴𝚡𝚙𝚕𝚊𝚗𝚊𝚝𝚒𝚘𝚗</mml:mtext></mml:math></alternatives></inline-formula>
  module and to draft certain docstring elements. For writing this
  manuscript and preparing supporting materials, generative AI was
  employed solely for formatting.</p>
</sec>
<sec id="acknowledgements">
  <title>Acknowledgements</title>
  <p>We would like to express our gratitude to Clément Bénard, Alexandre
  Chaussard and Vincent Auriau for their valuable help and feedback.</p>
</sec>
